  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "obtained I this freedom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Better “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "this citizenship",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Rev. Ver.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Probably at the time when the A. V. was made “freedom” conveyed somewhat of this sense as we speak still of bestowing on any one the “freedom” of a city, meaning thereby all the rights of a citizen. It was the Roman boast “I am a Roman ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "citizen",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",” (Cic. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in Verr",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". v. 63). The sale of the freedom of Rome was at times the perquisite of some of the Imperial parasites and favourites, who made what they could of such a privilege.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I was free born",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Rev. Ver.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " “I am a Roman born.” How St Paul came to be a Roman citizen by birth we cannot tell, probably some ancestor for meritorious conduct had been rewarded with enfranchisement. Tarsus was a free city, and had its own laws and magistrates, but that did not constitute its inhabitants Roman citizens.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
