  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 28.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "- Citizenship",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "freedom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "am a Roman",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "was free",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "A great sum",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "πολλοῦ κεφαλαίου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The word is only found here in the New Testament in the sense of a \"sum of money,\" but is so used in classical writers. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Citizenship",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "πολιτεία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for \"freedom of the city,\" in Xenophon, AElian, Polybius, Dion Cassius, etc., and 3Macc. 3:21. Dion Cassius (9 17) relates that Messaliua, the wife of the Emperor Claudius, used to sell the freedom of the city, and that at first she sold it (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "μεγάλων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ξρημάτων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") for a very high price, but that afterwards it became very cheap. In all probability Lysias had so purchased it, and in consequence took the name of Claudius (Renan, ' St. Paul,' p. 524). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I am a Roman born",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is not known how St. Paul's family acquired the Roman citizenship. Acts 22:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Sum (κεφαλαίου)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., capital. The purchase of Roman citizenship was an investment. Under the first Roman emperors it was obtained only at large cost and with great difficulty; later, it was sold for a trifle.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "I was free-born (ἐγὼ καὶ γεγέννημαι)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., I am even so born, leaving the mind to supply free or a Roman. Better, as Rev., I am a Roman born. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
